<h2>What Is a Technical SEO Audit?</h2>
<p>A technical SEO audit is a systematic review of your website's infrastructure to identify problems that prevent Google from crawling, indexing, and ranking your pages. While on-page SEO is about content, and off-page SEO is about authority, technical SEO is about the foundations — ensuring your website is structurally sound enough for Google to understand and trust it.</p>
<p>Many Kenyan businesses invest in content and advertising without fixing technical problems that are quietly strangling their rankings. A technical audit surfaces these issues so they can be fixed.</p>

<h2>What a Technical SEO Audit Covers</h2>
<h3>1. Crawlability and Indexability</h3>
<p>Can Google actually find and read all your pages? Problems here include:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Blocked pages in robots.txt that should be indexed</li>
  <li>Pages marked "noindex" by accident</li>
  <li>Broken internal links leading to 404 pages</li>
  <li>Incorrect XML sitemap (missing pages, broken URLs)</li>
  <li>Pages with no internal links pointing to them ("orphan pages")</li>
</ul>

<h3>2. Site Speed and Core Web Vitals</h3>
<p>Google uses Core Web Vitals as a direct ranking factor. An audit checks:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>LCP</strong> (Largest Contentful Paint) — is the main content loading in under 2.5 seconds?</li>
  <li><strong>INP</strong> (Interaction to Next Paint) — does the page respond to clicks/taps within 200ms?</li>
  <li><strong>CLS</strong> (Cumulative Layout Shift) — do elements jump around as the page loads?</li>
  <li>Image file sizes — uncompressed images are the #1 cause of slow Kenyan websites</li>
  <li>Render-blocking resources — JavaScript and CSS that delay page rendering</li>
  <li>Server response time — slow hosting is a common issue with budget Kenyan hosts</li>
</ul>

<h3>3. Mobile Usability</h3>
<p>Since Google uses mobile-first indexing, your mobile experience determines your rankings. An audit checks:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Are all pages fully responsive on small screens?</li>
  <li>Are tap targets (buttons, links) large enough and well-spaced?</li>
  <li>Is text readable without zooming?</li>
  <li>Are any elements wider than the screen (causing horizontal scroll)?</li>
</ul>

<h3>4. HTTPS and Security</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Is your SSL certificate valid and not expired?</li>
  <li>Are all pages served over HTTPS (not mixed HTTP/HTTPS content)?</li>
  <li>Are there any security headers missing (HSTS, X-Content-Type-Options)?</li>
</ul>

<h3>5. URL Structure and Duplicate Content</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Are your URLs clean and descriptive (e.g., /services/seo-kenya, not /page?id=42)?</li>
  <li>Does your site load correctly with and without "www" — and redirects to one canonical version?</li>
  <li>Is there duplicate content (same content on multiple URLs)?</li>
  <li>Are canonicals set correctly?</li>
</ul>

<h3>6. Structured Data (Schema Markup)</h3>
<p>Schema markup helps Google understand your content and can earn "rich results" — star ratings, FAQs, and event listings in search results that increase click-through rates. An audit checks whether you have:</p>
<ul>
  <li>LocalBusiness schema (name, address, phone, hours, coordinates)</li>
  <li>Organisation schema</li>
  <li>Product / Service schema (for e-commerce)</li>
  <li>Review / AggregateRating schema</li>
  <li>FAQ schema (for high-traffic content pages)</li>
</ul>

<h3>7. Google Search Console Errors</h3>
<p>Google Search Console (GSC) is Google's own tool for communicating issues with your site. An audit reviews GSC for:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Manual penalties</li>
  <li>Coverage errors (pages not indexed)</li>
  <li>Core Web Vitals issues flagged by Google</li>
  <li>Mobile usability errors</li>
  <li>Structured data errors</li>
</ul>

<h2>Common Technical SEO Issues Found on Kenyan Websites</h2>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Issue</th><th>How Common</th><th>SEO Impact</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Uncompressed images &gt; 1MB</td><td>Very common</td><td>High — slows LCP</td></tr>
    <tr><td>No SSL / expired certificate</td><td>Common</td><td>Very high — Google warns users</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Pages not in sitemap</td><td>Common</td><td>Medium — slower indexing</td></tr>
    <tr><td>No local schema markup</td><td>Very common</td><td>Medium — misses rich results</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Render-blocking JavaScript</td><td>Very common (WordPress)</td><td>High — delays page render</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Broken internal links</td><td>Common</td><td>Medium — confuses crawlers</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Duplicate title tags</td><td>Common</td><td>Medium — keyword cannibalisation</td></tr>
    <tr><td>No Google Search Console setup</td><td>Very common</td><td>Critical — no visibility into issues</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>What Happens After a Technical SEO Audit?</h2>
<p>An audit produces a prioritised list of issues. The typical priority order:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Critical</strong>: Indexability blocks, SSL issues, Google penalties — fix immediately</li>
  <li><strong>High</strong>: Core Web Vitals failures, broken pages, duplicate content — fix within 1–2 weeks</li>
  <li><strong>Medium</strong>: Missing schema, URL structure issues, missing GSC setup — fix within 1 month</li>
  <li><strong>Low</strong>: Minor optimisations — fix ongoing</li>
</ol>
<p>After fixes are implemented, Google typically needs 2–6 weeks to recrawl and update rankings.</p>

